arch:property.oc:show_val: A medium-sized unit with a very even light brown colour. There is a moderate amount of burning and a small amount of carnivore activity. Most of the unit is 03 size long bone fragments but there are some larger taxa, including red deer and pig, both represented by a single cranial piece. Most of the identifiable elements are caprine foot or cranial fragments. There is a small fragment of burnt turtle plastron. There are also two bone point fragments and a piece of burnt human skull. An additional dry sieve sample #5 was completely recorded and four >4mm flotation samples, 100% sorted, (#2, 3, 4 and 6) had only the diagnostics recorded. Like the material previously identified, a significant amount of digestion was found in all of the samples. These samples highlighted considerable spatial differences within the deposit. Flotation sample #2 had been almost completely burnt at low temperatures and contained further remains of turtle. All the other samples contained very few bones (maybe 1 or 2%) compared to about 99% in sample #2. Additionally sample #6 was much less fragmented than the others and this sample also contained a further 3 bone tools. Further evidence of pig was identified in sample #4. Occasional fish bones were found in the unburnt flotation samples and these appear to be larger than most found so far. Generally the samples contained a range of body parts, although phalanges were particularily well represented in samples 3 and 4 and skull fragments were common in sample #6. Overall, the fauna seems to suggest that the deposit was an accumulation of debris from a number of different events or locations. Weathering of the bones is minimal suggesting, however, that the material in the deposit was not exposed for long periods before the next load of rubbish was deposited. Last number = 267

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
